== The Five Hindrances and the Dzogchen Antidote

I hope you'll be able to relate, you know, not just sitting, but all four of these postures of walking, lying down, standing, and sitting. We usually have the five hindrances going on in all our situations throughout the day, actually. 

So what are the five hindrances, right? Maybe I should mention that first.

Well the first one is desire. The second one is ill will, anger, general aversion, think we could say. The third one would be laziness. The fourth one would restlessness. And the fifth one is doubt, particularly doubt in one's own capacity to be free. 

So if I was to briefly summarize each one, I guess I would say: desire keeps you off the cushion most of all. It's chasing shiny things and vivid sense pleasures that distract us into cycles of stress and disease. So this could also be on subtle levels where we desire a different state of consciousness---we want to feel different than we feel right now. It could be applied to all four foundations of mindfulness, actually. You don't want these thoughts; you don't want these feelings; we don't want this body stuff going on, whatever it may be. We don't want this environment, or something about this environment.

So I suppose that leads into the next one, which is ill will or aversion. So that's another one that can keep us off the cushion. We start to have an ill will towards the Dharma or Sanghas or the teachers. But also it's easy for our mind to get disgruntled in a position where we have a kind of subtle ill will in our internal narrative. Perhaps being judgmental or even all these discriminations that we hear about, but also towards ourselves, we have ill will. 

And then if we're very angry and destructive, then certainly we cannot practice the Dharma. We can't even sit and read a paragraph because we're so kind of riled up.

So the third one, laziness or torpor, kind of sloth. It's just kind of a half, 50% wanting liberation---not really wanting it all the way, and not really having much diligence, perhaps even missing some sincerity towards the path. So this will cause us to have insincere listening when it comes to the teachings and the advice on how to meditate. We'll basically be lazy about how we interpret those.

And so when it comes to being "on the cushion," we can fall asleep so easily or just check out and go watch some TV, you know?

So the next one would be restlessness. That can go hand in hand with anger and desire of course because if you've done something that you feel shameful about or regret or hurt somebody and possibly stole something or anything like that---well you will be restless. If you're worrying about the future typically the future brings a lot of anxiety to beings.

Of course, restlessness on the cushion is going to make you uncomfortable. Like I've been sitting here in full lotus this whole time, perfectly comfortable, because my mind, my thoughts, aren't running away, causing my nervous system to start to clench itself and things like that. 

So really, restlessness can cause a lot of discomfort during the sits. Those of you who are sitting longer---that will be an issue. So the content of your thoughts is very important. And remember, this applies to all the postures when we're out there in the world. So, restlessness... just having restlessness can end up being a factor in your communication, in your going to sleep at night, in your eating---all kinds of stuff. The five hindrances are all kind of distractions, in a way.

So the last one is doubt. And doubt; I think the primary there is doubt that you can even be free, that you can even have peace. Sometimes it takes a guide or a friend to remind us of that: that everything's going to be okay, that you are worthy of veneration.

You know the hierarchy that we see, the hierarchy of respect and veneration has always baffled me. Why wouldn't we venerate each other on the same level, in an egalitarian kind of way? If I say to you, "My mind is the All-Creating Monarch; I'm God," well you may immediately think, "Oh, he thinks he's God." To that I have a rebuttal: "God would not create this mess that I was in, and sometimes I'm still in."

So it's more the veneration: just why can't we respect each other like God? You know like you're a God; I'm a God. Praise: I praise your light, your beauty. See, so things like that where we empower each other again. This culture, this environment that we're in, the collective, can be incredibly... it can be incredibly disempowering.

#btw[Dawai reads a chat message]. It can't sound like Christianity, because that would be blasphemy in Christianity, saying that each individual is the God. No, not an image of God. Your mind is the All-Creating Monarch, and I feel like there's a lot more evidence of how our mind is creating this reality than, in fact, I would say there's proof not only in modern science, but also in all these Dharma lineages.

There's proof that our mind is the creator. There's a lot more proof and evidence in regards to that than there is that some external deity or being or force is creating the environment. The more I do my own mind science, the more I see: well, I don't need to conclude anything existentially, but I see that my mind has a huge role in the creation of my reality.

And just acknowledging that your mind has power, that your mind is involved in the creation of this reality to a significant degree, you don't need to speculate: "Is it creating all of it?" or "Is it divine?"Is it God?" "Is it…" See, all that is kind of conceptual proliferation that we don't need to apply.

It does have a kind of magic to it and divinity, certainly; but your lucid, subtle mind that's responsible for creating so much of this reality and holding it up. And when we start to settle into that lucid mind and understand our enjoyment body and our Buddha-nature, then we come into the true maturity of mind.

When we're just in the thinking mind and constantly needing ideas and beliefs and concepts to get by: well, it's a kind of spiritual immaturity. Ultimate peace can be found in pure silence, without a single thought or idea or concept. And it can be found in the concepts as well.

So I think doubt always, in Dzogchen, Vajrayana too, both in general: doubt can be a major hindrance for folks because enlightenment has a mystique. We actually take a lot of demystifying in here; we take on a lot of demystifying enlightenment in here. We make it accessible---that's what makes this group exceptional: that we're actually listening to the scriptures, listening to these yogis, these great yogis, and saying: well, if they're talking about enlightenment in one lifetime, or at least liberation, whatever that looks like, well many Dharma practitioners have made that unobtainium, have made that out of reach, or maybe in the next three or four lifetimes.

Well I feel like there's been too much spiritual abuse and people being misled for that kind of pie-in-the-sky approach. So we go for direct liberation, quickly; and as long as it's working, as my teacher Khenchen Tsewang Gyatso would say: "If compassion and wisdom are increasing, your approach is working."

And we have for some reason lost touch with the inspiration and the divine kind of hope that was given by the great masters like Tulku Urgyen Rinpoche, who said in the beginning of his book, Repeating the Words of the Buddha; in that book, he says: "Enlightenment is not some myth or fable; it actually does happen. I've known many people in my lifetime reaching such a state."

And somehow, his son, Mingyur Rinpoche, is continuing to uphold that tradition of passing out water to the thirsty, so to speak; yet we've kind of lost the spirit of that. I feel like Namkhai Norbu was also kind of anti-institutionalizing things: keeping it in the lineages, keeping it in the grassroots, and being part of this. There's an awakening happening to many beings.

So doubt can be in the path, you know, that this is even possible. That's why Tulku Urgyen Rinpoche actually remarked on that; because so many Dharma practitioners, just... they always had a subtle doubt, if not totally explicit. You know, it wasn't so subtle sometimes. But it can be a little block inside our mind that says: "Yeah, enlightenment; yeah, right," or "Me being in this Buddha state; yeah, right." And it usually takes us like defeating ourselves to make that possible.

So any comments, questions, sharing on the five hindrances, just a brief kind of summary of those?

We have many antidotes, and I'm going to talk about how to counter these now. We have many antidotes in Shravakayana, Mahayana, in the various approaches. There are antidotes to the five hindrances. 

We have practices like Chöd, which serve as an antidote to the five poisons. Breath meditation can serve as an antidote to the five hindrances.

Dawai reading chat: In Theravada Buddhism, overcoming the five hindrances equals jhana.

Dawai: Well, I would say that's a generalization, that it's very reductive. You know, you have many jhanas. What does overcoming the five hindrances mean? The five hindrances can still flicker in and out, even if you're able to achieve states of jhana.

So in Dzogchen, let's talk about this, you just let your five hindrances be, but you need mindfulness, awareness, you need the Sati, the Rigpa, the Vidya; so many names for it. You need this in order to let your desire, your anger, your laziness, your restlessness and doubt, to let it be. 

Otherwise, how are you going to let it be? You can't let your laziness be because you're in the laziness. You have nowhere to run. But if you've been introduced to awareness, you have somewhere to go. So you start to more and more access the pure presence.

How can there be restlessness in the pure presence? Until I start creating the future, worries about the future, etc. How can there be desire in the pure presence? Unless I get stuck on a thought and I say, "Oh, I need to go eat some pizza," or whatever.

And then I'll start to get anxious and my body will be sore, maybe, if you're sitting. Sometimes people just quit because of desire. So you know, the lower base, the bumpa breathing also helps, by the way, with the hindrances.

But as far as laxity... it's laxity, right? Kind of laziness. This is also left alone you know, but a lot of people get sleepy during the meditations. And that's because we follow a thought. We follow a thought, and a lot of people have their eyes closed, so the body's saying, "Oh, sleepy time." And so we're kind of following that thought with our eyes closed, and next thing you know, goodbye, or good night.

So in the pure presence, wakefulness, there are no thoughts to drag you off into the hypnagogic state, the transitory state before sleep, I guess that's a bardo.

So restlessness: let’s say we come here and do the 10-minute sit in the beginning, and we feel very anxious for whatever reason. It could be because somebody yelled at us; it could be because we hurt somebody by accident. You know, it could be anything. Well, letting that be, giving a little bit of a chance for your nervous system to relax—even the lobes of the brain, everything’s starting to release tension—that restlessness released within awareness.

Now doubt is a little bit more of an a priori, kind of logic related thing that could help many of you to rely on your past proofs that you've had through these meditations, these approaches, and use that as a stepping stone for trust.

Never ever blind-trust things, unless you're very confident in somebody as your guide and you trust what they say, then I don't think that's blind, though. I think that's well-informed, because you've gotten to know this person.

But it's important I think, in our culture, these days and these times, to continue to step on the evidences and proofs that you've had previously from meditation, or from Dzogchen, so that doubt is cleared away; because doubt can follow us very far along the path. It can follow us all the way to the tippy-top, you know. It can hold us back from that final release, even.

Okay, so, yeah, it's just a little brief summary of the five hindrances: how they can look in Dzogchen. Any other comments or sharing or questions?

And by the way, refuge and bodhicitta—doing it silently—is good for the hindrances, too. If you can, at the beginning of the sit, take refuge in your awareness nature; kind of really relax into it. If you can wish all beings to have liberation and rest in that kind of love for all beings: the natural pulse of your energy.

It kind of just... you don't pick and choose beings that you love. The love is just like the sun radiating heat. You're radiating compassion, and not the kind of love that we deal with sometimes on superficial levels. I'm talking about profound, empathetic, all-encompassing, unconditional love.

So refuge and bodhicitta are also helpful in terms of the hindrances. As I said, pranayama, breathing exercises, yoga, staying hydrated and rested, of course, things like that can always benefit.

